Key Finding

General Commercial (GC) zoning is not compatible with the NAC future land use designation. The property operates under grandfathered/nonconforming status tied to the existing business license for "Lawn Equipment & Small Engine Repair."

Section 02

Grandfathering

The property's current use is protected under Cobb County's nonconforming use provisions. This grandfathered status allows the existing lawn equipment and small engine repair operation to continue despite the zoning/FLU incompatibility.

Grandfathering Rules

Rule Requirement Implication
Vacancy Limit 6 months maximum Business license must stay active or new owner must re-activate within 6 months of closing
Expansion Prohibited Cannot add SF or intensity beyond current footprint
Ownership Transfer Survives sale New owner inherits status IF they continue the licensed use
Similar Use Flexibility Likely permitted Small engine/equipment repair may extend to similar service uses (golf carts, UTVs, outdoor power equipment)

Buyer Pathways

Buyer Intent Path Zoning Action Risk Level
Continue lawn/small engine repair Grandfathered GC None required Low
Similar equipment service (golf carts, power sports) Grandfathered GC None required Medium
Different use entirely Rezone to NRC Rezoning application Medium
Critical Note

The GC zoning is essentially a shellit only protects the specific grandfathered use on the business license. Any buyer pursuing a different use must rezone to an NAC-compatible district (most likely NRC).

Section 03

Future Land Use Restrictions NAC

The property is located within a Neighborhood Activity Center (NAC) as designated by the Cobb County Comprehensive Plan. This future land use designation controls which zoning districts can be approved.

NAC-Compatible Zoning Districts

District Name Compatibility
SC Suburban Condominium Compatible
LRO Low Rise Office Compatible
LRC Low Rise Commercial Compatible
OS Office Service Special Exception
NRC Neighborhood Retail Commercial Compatible
RSL Residential Senior Living Compatible

Non-Compatible Districts

District Name Status
GC General Commercial (current) Not Compatible
LI Light Industrial Not Compatible
HI Heavy Industrial Not Compatible
LI Rezoning Not Viable

While the property's physical characteristics (warehouse, auto lifts, compressed air) align with Light Industrial uses, LI zoning is not compatible with the NAC future land use designation. A rezoning to LI would require a Comprehensive Plan Amendment to change the FLU designationa lengthy process with uncertain approval given neighborhood opposition.

Section 04

NRC Most Flexible Zoning District Approved Within NAC

The Neighborhood Retail Commercial (NRC) district is the most permissive zoning classification compatible with the NAC overlay. It provides the broadest range of commercial uses while maintaining neighborhood scale and character.

NRC Purpose & Intent

Per Cobb County Code Section 134-213, NRC is established to provide locations for convenience shopping facilities with retail commercial uses that have a neighborhood-oriented market and which supply necessities that usually require frequent purchasing with minimum consumer travel.

  • Special Exception Uses: 35-foot landscaped screening buffer required

Key Insight

The 47% warehouse ratio (6,356 SF of 13,603 SF) is the parking safety valve. As long as buyers preserve the warehouse-heavy mix, parking works. The more showroom/retail or repair they activate, the tighter it gets.

Use Profile Details

1. Equipment Dealer (Sales + Light Service)

Natural fit for building layout. Showroom in front, service in back. "Nonautomotive repair" covers small engine, lawn equipment, golf carts, UTVs. Building B at 4,185 SF is under the 8,000 SF cap for repair uses. Auto lifts and compressed air are assets.

  • Parking works if service area remains classified as warehouse
  • No outside storage of equipment or inventory
  • No outdoor repair work

2. Trade Showroom + Warehouse

Heavy warehouse component keeps parking requirement low. Showroom for contractor/retail customers, bulk storage in back. Clean NRC fit as "neighborhood retail."

  • 5 drive-in bays excellent for contractor pickup/delivery
  • No service/repair component to complicate parking
  • Avoid "farm and garden supply" classification (1/100 SF ratio)

3. Contractor Headquarters

Office component is small, warehouse-heavy ratio keeps parking low. Indoor storage of materials/equipment is permitted. Compressed air hookups useful for tool maintenance. Auto lifts could service company fleet vehicles (incidental to primary use).

  • 31 space surplus accommodates fleet vehicles if parked on-site
  • "Contractor (specialized) without heavy equipment" may be special exception
  • Verify adjacent zoning for buffer requirement

4. Light Auto Repair + Parts Retail

Building B is under the 8,000 SF cap. Auto lifts already in place. Works if front building is repositioned as less retail-intensive (more warehouse classification).

  • No outside repair except taillights, wipers, batteries, tires
  • Adjacent to residential requires noise abatement measures
  • Every vehicle on-site must be in a striped parking space

Prohibited Uses

The following uses are either explicitly prohibited in NRC, practically impossible due to parking requirements, or blocked by regulatory moratoriums.

Explicitly Prohibited in NRC

Use Reason
Heavy Auto Repair Not in NRC permitted use table
Warehouse/Distribution (Primary) Not permitted as standalone use
Outside Storage Explicitly prohibited
Fleet Vehicle Staging No overnight commercial vehicle parking (except minivans/cars)
Laboratories or Clinics Explicitly prohibited
Sexually Oriented Businesses Explicitly prohibited
Uses with Noxious Odors/Fumes/Sounds Explicitly prohibited

Prohibited by Moratorium

Use Reason
Self-Service Storage Facility (SSSF) No new SLUP applications accepted since January 1, 1998
Storage is Dead

Self-service storage is technically listed as a permitted use in NRC but requires an SLUP. The county has refused new SLUP applications for storage since 1998making this a "zombie use" that's on the books but inaccessible.

Section 07

Rezoning Process

For buyers pursuing a use not covered by the grandfathered status, rezoning to NRC is the most viable path. The process takes approximately 2 months from complete filing to Board of Commissioners decision.

Timeline Overview

1
File Complete Application
First Thursday of month by 4:00 PM
2
Applicant Meeting with Staff
~10 days after filing deadline
3
Mail Notice to Owners within 1,000 ft
30 days before PC hearing (postmark date)
4
Proof of Mailing Due
21 days before PC hearing
5
Planning Commission Hearing
First Tuesday, 2 months after filing
6
Board of Commissioners Hearing
Third Tuesday, same month as PC hearing

Application Fees

Item Amount Notes
Application Fee (0-20,000 SF, commercial) $900 Based on 13,603 SF existing building
Sign Deposit $300 Refundable if returned within 30 days
Sign Fee (per sign) $15 Non-refundable
Total Estimated ~$1,230
Septic Approval Already Complete

Properties on septic require approval from Cobb County Public Health prior to filing a rezoning application. This property's septic system (1,000 gallon) has already been reviewed and approved by the Environmental Health District, satisfying this requirement.

Required Submittals

  • Notarized application with titleholder signature
  • Warranty deed (current owner)
  • Legal description of property
  • Paid tax receipt
  • Stamped site plan (engineer/surveyor sealed) with all required elements
  • Written zoning impact analysis addressing 6 statutory criteria
  • Property/financial disclosure forms
  • Campaign contribution disclosure forms

Statutory Criteria for Approval

The written impact analysis must address:

  1. Whether the zoning proposal will permit a use suitable in view of adjacent property use and development
  2. Whether the proposal will adversely affect existing use or usability of adjacent property
  3. Whether the property has reasonable economic use as currently zoned
  4. Whether the proposal will cause excessive burden on streets, transportation, utilities, or schools
  5. Whether the proposal is in conformity with the Comprehensive Plan
  6. Whether other existing or changing conditions support approval or disapproval
No Traffic Study Required

Traffic impact studies are only required for projects exceeding 50,000 SF of non-residential space. This property at 13,603 SF is well under the threshold.

Section 08

Changes Ahead: Cobb County UDC Initiative

What is the Unified Development Code (UDC)?

Cobb County is undertaking a comprehensive rewrite of its development regulations through the Unified Development Code (UDC) project. The UDC will consolidate regulations currently scattered across multiple chapters of the County Codeincluding Chapter 134 (Zoning), Chapter 110 (Subdivision), Chapter 66 (Historic Preservation), and Chapter 58 (Floods)into a single, integrated, easy-to-use document.

Why This Matters

Cobb County's current zoning ordinance was drafted in the 1970s for a county of approximately 200,000 residents. Today, Cobb County has nearly 800,000 residents. After decades of piecemeal amendments, the regulations are poorly organized, internally inconsistent, and lack features of modern codes. The UDC project aims to modernize these regulations while preserving existing neighborhoods and supporting the County's Comprehensive Plan.

Key Change: Expanded NRC Uses

More Flexibility Coming for NRC Properties

Under the proposed UDC, the number of permitted uses in the NRC district is expected to expand. This could provide additional flexibility for properties like 2140 Canton Road, potentially allowing uses that are currently prohibited or require special exception approval. Property owners and buyers should monitor the UDC drafts as they are released to understand how these changes may affect development options.

Project Status

Installment Two of the UDC was released in November 2025, including:

  • Reorganized and restructured zoning districts
  • Reorganized uses and use regulations
  • New mixed-use districts
  • New Planned Development district

Installment Three (expected early 2026) will include:

  • Updated parking standards
  • Landscaping requirements
  • Lighting standards
  • Sign regulations
  • Enforcement and development standards

Impact on This Property

Until the UDC is formally adopted, the current zoning regulations (Chapter 134) and rezoning procedures remain in effect. The analysis in this document is based on the current NRC district regulations and NAC overlay requirements.

Property owners and buyers should monitor the UDC project for potential changes to:

  • Parking ratios and requirements
  • Use definitions and classifications
  • Buffer and landscaping standards
  • Activity center policies
